\begin{frame}{Overview: data types}
\onslide<+->
\vspace{-1em}
\scriptsize In order of coercion \onslide<+-> (if mixed, TRUE is converted to 1,~  3.14 to "3.14" etc)
\vspace{-0.7em}
\small
<<coercion, eval=FALSE, echo=FALSE>>=
l <- list(null=NULL, na=NA, logi=TRUE, factor=as.factor("hi"), int=7L, double=3.14,
          complex=5+3i, char="hello", time=Sys.time(), date=as.Date("2017-05-02"), func=ncol)
sapply(l, function(x) c(mode=mode(x), typeof=typeof(x), class=class(x)[1]))
sapply(l, function(x) sapply(l, function(y)  class(c(x,y))[1] ))
sapply(l, function(x) sapply(l, function(y) typeof(c(x,y)) ))
@
\begin{center}
\begin{tabu}{| l | l | l | l |}   \hline
\uncover<+->{Description      & example         & \rcode{typeof} & \rcode{class}     \\ \hline  \hline}
\uncover<+->{empty set        & NULL                 & NULL      & NULL              \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{not available    & NA                   & logical   & logical           \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{logical          & c(T, F, FALSE, TRUE) & logical   & logical           \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{category         & factor("left")       & integer   & \textbf{factor}   \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{integer number   & 4:6  ; 7L            & integer   & integer           \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{decimal          & 8.7                  & double    & \textbf{numeric}  \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{complex          & 5+3i                 & complex   & complex           \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{character string & "homer rocks"        & character & character         \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{time             & Sys.time()           & double    & \textbf{POSIXct}  \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{date             & as.Date("2017-05-02")& double    & \textbf{Date}     \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{function         & ncol                 & closure   & \textbf{function} \\ \hline}
\end{tabu}
\end{center}
\vspace{-1em}
\scriptsize
\onslide<+->
\href{http://adv-r.had.co.nz/Data-structures.html}{adv-r.had.co.nz/Data-structures}.
\onslide<+->
%See also e.g. Uwe Ligges (2006) - Programmieren mit R\\
\rcode{as.character}\texttt{(3.14)} converts a data type;  \onslide<+-> \rcode{is.integer}\texttt{(4:6)} checks. \onslide<+->
\rcode{str} shows an abbreviation of \rcode{class}. \onslide<+->
\rcode{mode} (for users) is like \rcode{typeof} (R internal), but combines
integer and double to numeric (\& closure, special and builtin to function). \onslide<+->
Other rare typeofs: raw, environment, promise, ... \onslide<+->
When mixing date/time with others, the order of appearance determines the output class.
\label{datatypes}
\end{frame}

%------------------------------------------------------------%

\begin{frame}{Overview: Object types}
\vspace{-2em}
\begin{center}
%\begin{tabu}{| l | m{4cm} | m{3cm} | l |}  \hline
\begin{tabu}{| l | l | l | l |}  \hline
\uncover<+->{Object     & example                                   & \rcode{typeof}      & \rcode{class}\\ \hline   \hline}
\uncover<+->{vector     & \textit{see data types}                   & ...                 & ...          \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{matrix     & matrix(9:15, ncol=2)                      & ...                 & matrix       \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{array      & array(letters[1:24], dim=c(2,6,4))        & ...                 & array        \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{data.frame & \small data.frame(C1=4:5, C2=c("a","b"))  & list                & data.frame   \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{list       & list(el1=7:15, el2="big")                 & list                & list         \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{function   & function(x) 12+0.5*x                      & closure             & function     \\ \hline}
\uncover<+->{...        & lm(b $\sim$ a)                            & list                & lm           \\ \hline}
\end{tabu}
\end{center}
\vspace{-0.5em}
\small
\onslide<+->
A \rcode{matrix} consists of only one data type. \onslide<+->
If you accidentally change one element to a character, all are converted \onslide<+-> and calculations are not possible any more
(See coercion order in previous slide).\\
\onslide<+-> \rcode{data.frame}s can have multiple data types, \onslide<+-> but a column in itself also has only one type.\\
\onslide<+-> \rcode{list}s can combine anything, even other lists.\\
\onslide<+-> \rcode{is.atomic}\texttt{(Object)} returns TRUE (vector, matrix, array) or FALSE\\
\onslide<+-> \rcode{as.matrix}\texttt{(Object)} converts the class of an object by force.
\end{frame}

